			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Thanks for a quick reaction...
<br />
I've been on holiday not IRC.
<br />

<br />
About the survival rates, I suggested bonus for defender + penalty for attacker, so that should mean commies die. Idea is that a top guy who hits down and always wins has a <span style="font-style: italic">reasonable</span> chance of losing commies if any of his fleets get knocked out ('cos 100% survival is lame) and it's a massacre if he loses ! And the middle guy who's getting hit regularly on defenses doesn't always come away with only 1/2 to 2/3 of his lvl-20 commies even with escape pods.
<br />

<br />
I'm pretty sure you've not often been on the wrong end of the survival penalty for losing a battle, but I can assure you that if you're producing 1-2 doom/tick and so getting purged by the top using full armadas every 1-2 days, you get through a hell of a lot of lvl-20 commies ! It makes keeping 20 available for your fleets hard, let alone decent ones. It's already enough of a penalty needing to put escape pods in your designs and generally fighting with only 500-600 dooms against 720-750, but having to struggle to get enough lvl-20s to make a proper armada too is downright depressing  <img src="images/smiles/icon_evil.gif" alt="Evil or Very Mad" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
PS Come on, how many attacks did you lose last set ? One, for the loss of how many commies ? And how many commies in victories... not many I'd guess. Smarty implied that he lost only 4 or 5 commies all set when the Empire hit returning expeditions and ally ships (in thread about ending scores). Over large parts of last set, I was losing an average of 4 or 5 lvl-20s day to regular purges by full armadas every 1-2 days.
<br />

<br />
How about something to favour the people who get hit by the bigger guys all the time... and maybe reduce that bonus/penalty for winning/losing a battle. It ought to be a lot easier to rescue your commie in system even if you lose !</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
