			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I agree strongly with the general idea of bonus for defender, penalty for the attacker when it comes to commander loss. Because all attacks are directed at planets, either for taking them over, raiding them, etc etc, the defense fleet is logically in orbit or close to the planet, especially if they're stationed at that planet. Any attacking fleet that gets blown up should have a very low chance of commander survival, but only if they lose the battle. The defender has a higher rate of commander survival, win or lose. If a fleet blows up and the commander gets out, the planet is a mighty good target for landing the escape pod, getting away from battle. Whether or not the enemy takes over the planet, a commander could most likely land, get an actual transport ship and skip planet to avoid death... yeah...
<br />

<br />
One feature that would be possibly difficult to pull off but make sense regards how quickly the fleet is destroyed. If your fleet is taken out instantly in a wave of black hole death, the commander has no warning and no chance to escape... but if your fleet is being slowly picked to death by lighter weapons over the course of a number of turns, any smart commander would start heading for the escape pod when his or her ship started to get pretty battered... possibly even get away before the ship was taken down. Hehe, then you get the embarassed commander who has to ask to be tractor-beamed back into the ship. "Sorry guys, I thought you were all going to die, so I was getting out ASAP. ...will you open the airlock already?"</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
